&lt;/script&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;img src="//feeds.feedburner.com/~r/WritersAndAuthors/~4/KWhBzsWKzao" height="1" width="1" alt=""/&gt;</content><link rel="replies" type="application/atom+xml" href="http://www.writersandauthors.info/feeds/5206919876846832051/comments/default" title="Post Comments" /><link rel="replies" type="text/html" href="http://www.writersandauthors.info/2014/11/interview-with-nata-romeo.html#comment-form" title="0 Comments" /><link rel="edit" type="application/atom+xml" href="http://www.blogger.com/feeds/12022998072736925/posts/default/5206919876846832051" /><link rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" href="http://www.blogger.com/feeds/12022998072736925/posts/default/5206919876846832051" /><link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/WritersAndAuthors/~3/KWhBzsWKzao/interview-with-nata-romeo.html" title="Interview with Nata Romeo" /><author><name>Jo Linsdell</name><uri>https://plus.google.com/101828877006458875410</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email><gd:image rel="http://schemas.google.com/g/2005#thumbnail" width="32" height="32" src="//lh3.googleusercontent.com/-jNRmf9Oer_g/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAARt8/U-hvuDdciwU/s512-c/photo.jpg" /></author><media:thumbnail xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-Gmcllc8Qis4/U-ej5uZjPcI/AAAAAAAAQs8/Gj3bIlDudEQ/s72-c/cover.png" height="72" width="72" /><thr:total>0</thr:total><feedburner:origLink>http://www.writersandauthors.info/2014/11/interview-with-nata-romeo.html</feedburner:origLink></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-12022998072736925.post-4175366724436881268</id><published>2014-11-10T07:00:00.000+01:00</published><updated>2014-11-10T07:00:00.162+01:00</updated><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="advice for authors" /><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="advice for writers" /><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="books" /><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="inspiration" /><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Moonlight Weeps" /><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="partners in crime tours" /><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Vincent Zandri" /><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="writers and authors" /><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="writing" /><title type="text">Inspiration</title><content type="html">&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-eb5Pz-TdaR4/VFEtKQk23hI/AAAAAAAAR-4/PVrzUFKcUCs/s1600/Moonlight-weeps-down-and-out.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="clear: right; float: right; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-eb5Pz-TdaR4/VFEtKQk23hI/AAAAAAAAR-4/PVrzUFKcUCs/s1600/Moonlight-weeps-down-and-out.jpg" height="320" width="213" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN-US"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;"&gt;Iâve written 16 books at last count. No, thatâs not right. Iâve published, or am about to publish my 16th novel come January of 2015. Iâve written far more than 16 (more like 22), and whatâs even more amazing to me, is that most of these were written between 2009 and the present day. When you consider I wrote my first full-length novel back in 1997 as a part of my creative thesis for my MFA in Writing at Vermont College, and that in those days my goal was to write one novel per year, I have been increasing my output in direct relation to the annual increase in my age. That said, I am now writing two to three 50-60,000 word novels per year, plus a novella or two tossed in. Add to that some journalism and blogging for the &lt;a href="http://vincentzandri.blogspot.it/"&gt;The Vincent Zandri Vox&lt;/a&gt;, and youâre taking a ton of words on a daily basis.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN-US"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;"&gt;A friend of mine who frequents the same bar I visit on a nightly basis when living in Florence, Italy in the Fall, always asks me the same question. âDid you write a new novel today?â Naturally, I laugh at this, but heâs not far off the mark considering the modern world of digital publishing and the demand readers (especially e-book readers) have placed on novelists to produce more and more work. My friend who, like me, will dress in black leather coat over jeans and combat boots in chilly Florence, often asks me how I can keep up such a pace. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN-US"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;"&gt;âWhere do you get your inspiration?â he asks. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN-US"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;"&gt;Once upon a time, I would have shrugged my shoulders, and smiled dumbly.&amp;nbsp; But now I approach the question by asking another question:&amp;nbsp; âWhere do you get yours?â&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN-US"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;"&gt;The man is a professor of math and science at a local university. Heâs expected to show up every day, rain or shine, to teach his students what they are paying him to learn. The inspiration required to get out of bed every morning, get dressed, and get himself to class is a moot point. If he canât do that, he needs another line of work, or he needs to see a shrink, pronto. Inspired teaching, however, is another thing altogether. But if one is good at oneâs jobâ¦if one possesses a certain degree of talentâ¦one then uses that talent as a channel for inspiration and creativity. This is what separates a professional from an amateur. The former being one who shows up for work every day, regardless of what is going on in the world and in his life. The latter being someone who works only when, âinspired.â This kind of inspired writer usually ends up being a writing teacher in order to pay the bills. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN-US"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;"&gt;Vincent Zandri is a professional writer.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN-US"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;"&gt;I work everyday. Two shifts usually. The first begins immediately when I wake up. I go from about seven to ten, when Iâll break for a workout. Then Iâll clean up, have lunch and work all afternoon and quit between five or six. I do this five days a week and on Saturday, Iâll try and work half a day. I take Sundays off, unless Iâm working on deadline. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN-US"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;"&gt;Writing is my job. Sometimes Iâm inspired to do it better than other times. Sometimes, inspiration never enters the equation. All too often Iâll look at what Iâve written at the end of the day and Iâll feel myself smiling because itâs not only good, it seems better than what I am capable of. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN-US"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;"&gt;âDid I write that?â Iâll whisper to myself.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-xGMHgWNfq6Y/VFEtu44psEI/AAAAAAAAR_A/GYp0o7t4Sgk/s1600/JP1_5294-1.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-xGMHgWNfq6Y/VFEtu44psEI/AAAAAAAAR_A/GYp0o7t4Sgk/s1600/JP1_5294-1.jpg" height="200" width="133" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span lang="EN-US"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;"&gt;Vincent Zandri is The New York Times and USA Today Bestselling Author of &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;span lang="EN-US"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;"&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.amazon.com/The-Remains-Vincent-Zandri-ebook/dp/B0073I2QHM/ref=pd_sim_sbs_kstore_1?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;refRID=1ZZSGESB577JD1NPHTYZ"&gt;&lt;b&gt;The Remains&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;b&gt;, &lt;/b&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.amazon.com/The-Remains-Vincent-Zandri-ebook/dp/B0073I2QHM/ref=pd_sim_sbs_kstore_1?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;refRID=1ZZSGESB577JD1NPHTYZ"&gt;&lt;b&gt;The Shroud Key&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;b&gt;, The Innocent, The Dick Moonlight PI series, and the forthcoming &lt;/b&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.amazon.com/Everything-Burns-Vincent-Zandri-ebook/dp/B00KYVKDWU%3FSubscriptionId%3D1QZMGW0RRJC2PX87HDR2%26tag%3Dsalranexp-20%26linkCode%3Dxm2%26camp%3D2025%26creative%3D165953%26creativeASIN%3DB00KYVKDWU"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Everything Burns&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;b&gt; from Thomas &amp;amp; Mercer. He has worked as a construction laborer, a car parker, a pizza delivery man, a sports reporter, and other odd jobs. Having earned his MFA in Writing from Vermont College, he is a freelance photojournalist, a world traveler, and the author/editor of the popular blog, &lt;/b&gt;&lt;a href="http://vincentzandri.blogspot.it/"&gt;&lt;b&gt;THE VINCENT ZANDRI VOX&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;"&gt;. He divides his time between New York and Florence, Italy. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN-US"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN-US"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;"&gt;GIVEAWAY&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="MsoNormal"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;script src="//s7.addthis.com/js/300/addthis_widget.js#pubid=xa-51adb6a4646b451d" type="text/javascript"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;&lt;script type="text/javascript"&gt;document.doAT = function(cl) {         var myclass = new RegExp('hentry');         var myTitleContainer = new RegExp('post-title');         var myPostContent = new RegExp('post-footer');         var elem = this.getElementsByTagName('div');            var url;         var title = "";                  for (var i = 0; i &lt; elem.length; i++)         {             var classes = elem[i].className;             if (myclass.test(classes))             {                 var container = elem[i];              url = window.location.href;                               for (var b = 0; b &lt; container.childNodes.length; b++)                 {                     var item = container.childNode